                                "elements": [
                                    {
                                        "type": "text",
                                        "text": "It's weird to hear both of you dismissing APL as a mess not even worth learning, and then discussing computing as a tool for thought a few minutes later. The link between the topic should be obvious from just the title of Ken Iverson's Turing Award lecture, \""
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "link",
                                        "url": "https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1145\/358896.358899",
                                        "text": "Notation as a tool of thought"
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "emoji",
                                        "name": "null"
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "link",
                                        "url": "https:\/\/apis.ebsco.com\/public\/linkout\/v1\/ftf?ref=79c1a803-bf3b-412a-9841-5283f3cceab1&id=627071",
                                        "text": "\""
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "text",
                                        "text": ", which I definitely recommend everybody to read. APL was designed as a mathematical notation for algorithmic problems, and only later turned into an executable notation at IBM. It is certainly not, and was never meant to be, a language for writing large software systems. But for its intended problem domain, it still is a good choice."
                                    }
                                ]
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "rich_text_section",
                                "elements": [
                                    {
                                        "type": "text",
                                        "text": "Programming languages not based on English are indeed rare, but there are a few interesting examples beyond just translating keywords. "
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "link",
                                        "url": "https:\/\/wy-lang.org\/",
                                        "text": "文言 (wenyan)"
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "text",
                                        "text": "  is based on classical Chinese that tries to incorporate even its grammar. "
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "link",
                                        "url": "https:\/\/web.eecs.umich.edu\/~imarkov\/Perligata.html",
                                        "text": "Perligata"
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "text",
                                        "text": " similarly takes inspiration from Latin grammar to build a Perl-like language on something pretty close to Latin (though not being \"good\" Latin, neither in vocabulary nor grammar). For those who read French, the "
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "link",
                                        "url": "https:\/\/codesource.hypotheses.org\/files\/2025\/01\/BMeles-Programmer_autres_langues.pdf",
                                        "text": "slides of a presentation by Baptiste Mélès"
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "text",
                                        "text": " say something about both these projects (I think the presentation was recorded, but I can't find it anywhere). "
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "link",
                                        "url": "https:\/\/hedy.org\/",
                                        "text": "Hedy"
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "text",
                                        "text": " by "
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "user",
                                        "user_id": "U08HASUA7KQ"
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "type": "text",
                                        "text": " and coworkers is a very different take on this topic: a language meant to make programming accessible to people from various cultural backgrounds."
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
